{
  "text": "The 4D theory we are trying to model is QCD with three massless quark flavours, possessing a global SU(3) L × SU(3) R symmetry which is spontaneously broken down to the vector subgroup via the quark condensate. [CITATION_1] The AdS/CFT correspondence then immediately tells us that the dual 5D theory should be a Yang-Mills theory with SU(3) L × SU(3) R gauge group, with a bi-fundamental bulk scalar field to provide breaking of this symmetry. The gauge fields in 5D couple to the QCD flavour currents whereas the bulk scalar couples to the bilinear quark operator. In previous models, the inclusion of a bulk scalar field allowed a comprehensive description of chiral symmetry breaking [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] [CITATION_4] [CITATION_5] . However, it is possible to take a limit of this theory where the entire description of chiral symmetry breaking is encoded into the boundary conditions imposed on the gauge fields [CITATION_6] [CITATION_7] and the holographic theory contains only gauge fields in the bulk. This simplified holographic dual model turns out to be a reasonable approximation [CITATION_8] [CITATION_9] , giving good results at least at the level of the two-point functions. The reason is that the condensate is an infrared (IR) effect, so that its influence can be modeled by an IR boundary condition. The complexity of the calculation of four-point current correlators in AdS/QCD means that this simpler form of holographic QCD, with only gauge fields in the bulk, provides an important starting point that can then be further refined.",
  "correct_citation": {
    "[CITATION_1]": "119380008",
